					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">Thanks for the input guys. I've tried shifting the comparison to +1 or -1. No joy yet. But at the same time, I've just noticed that while I pass a lot of blargg's APU tests. I also fail a few similar ones that I found in the nesticide test roms. So perhaps I have something subtly off which is close enough to pass some tests, but wrong enough to throw off some other tests. Either way, I will continue to test and experiment with the implementation to see what I need to do. I kinda feel it's a combination of factors right now, we'll see <img src="./images/smilies/icon_smile.gif" alt=":-)" title="Smile" />.<br /><br />Regarding why I'm doing the lazy evaluation, I'm sorry to say, it's not anything too exciting. I am currently simply not using a catch up method at all. I instead have implemented the CPU, PPU and APU such that they can be asked to execute 1 cycle at a time, and am running them lock step.<br /><br />I know this isn't the most efficient approach (I still get 350 FPS though, so it isn't too bad), but I want to make the implementation accurate and simple before I make it fast. On average, the catch up method is a little more complex to get right (at least IMO). The lazy evaluation allows me to choose to apply the reload or not later on. So far, this is the only case I've needed to do this though.<br /><br />Once I have the implementation correct, I plan to move towards the catchup method as an optimization though. Just not right now.<br /><br />Thanks again for the input.<br /><br />proxy</div>

